	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">User:LeonorBarroca</h1>
	<div id="bodyContent">
		<h3 id="siteSub">From SPA Wiki</h3>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="./index.php?title=User:LeonorBarroca&amp;useskin=bio#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="./index.php?title=User:LeonorBarroca&amp;useskin=bio#searchInput">search</a></div>
		<!-- start content -->
<p>I work for the OU and have been teaching and researching on software engineering for too many years to count. At the moment my focal questions are:
</p>
<ul><li> How to evolve decomposition of requirements into designs?
</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><ol><li> Choosing requirements decompositions with clear trade-offs in terms of software evolution;
</li><li> Providing representation schemes that facilitate the mapping to architectures.
</li></ol>
</dd></dl>
</dd></dl>
<ul><li> Can development with components cope with rapid change by expressing variation points through connectors?
</li><li> Can we separate what is more stable in a domain of application from what is more likely to change and evolve?
</li><li> Can we define stable components that can be put together in different configurations with different connectors that express variability?
</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><ol><li> Can domain analysis be matched to architectures, components and connectors?
</li><li> Does composition of components match composition of requirements?
</li><li> Is component-based development/PLs compatible with Agile development?
</li></ol>
</dd></dl>
</dd></dl>
<h4> <span class="mw-headline" id="Details"> Details </span></h4>
<p><b>Work:</b> <a href="http://computing.open.ac.uk/home/" class="external text" rel="nofollow">The Open University</a>
</p><p><b>Email:</b> l.barroca at open.ac.uk
</p><p><b>Web:</b> <a href="http://mcs.open.ac.uk/lmb3" class="external free" rel="nofollow">http://mcs.open.ac.uk/lmb3</a>
</p>
